.TH GIT-STAGE-BATCH 1 "March 2026" "git-stage-batch @VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
git-stage-batch \- hunk-by-hunk and line-by-line staging for git
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B git-stage-batch
[\fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR...]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B git-stage-batch
provides a workflow for staging changes to git in a structured, reviewable way.
The tool works by finding hunks in your diff, presenting them one at a time,
and letting you include (stage), skip, or discard each hunk.
.PP
State is maintained in \fB.git/git-stage-batch/\fR so you can stop and continue
later, or run git commands between operations.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS Core Operations
.TP
.B start
Find and display the first unprocessed hunk; cache as "selected".
Resets state if a session is already in progress.
.RS
.TP
.B \-U \fIN\fR, \-\-unified=\fIN\fR
Number of context lines in diff output (default: 3).
.RE
.TP
.B show \fR[\fB\-\-porcelain\fR]
Reprint the cached "selected" hunk.
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-porcelain
Exit silently with status code only (0 if hunk exists, 1 if no hunk).
Useful for scripts checking hunk availability without output.
.RE
.TP
.B include
Stage the cached hunk (entire hunk) to the index; advance to next.
When a session is active, running
.B git-stage-batch
with no command defaults to
.BR include .
.TP
.B skip
Mark the cached hunk as skipped; advance to next.
Skipped hunks can be revisited with
.BR again .
.TP
.B discard
Reverse-apply the cached hunk to the working tree; advance to next.
.B WARNING:
This permanently removes changes from your working tree.
.TP
.B status \fR[\fB\-\-porcelain\fR]
Show session progress and remaining hunks.
Displays iteration number, selected hunk location, progress metrics
(included/skipped/discarded/remaining counts), and a list of skipped hunks.
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-porcelain
Output in machine-readable JSON format for script integration.
The JSON includes: session (iteration and in_progress flag), selected
(selected hunk location or null), progress (counts), and skipped_hunks (array).
.RE
.SS Session Management
.TP
.B again
Clear the blocklist and restart iteration through all hunks.
Useful for making another pass after committing some changes.
.TP
.B stop
End the selected session and remove all state.
.TP
.B abort
Undo all changes made during the session, including commits and discards.
This resets HEAD to where you started, restores your original working tree,
restores batch state (drops created batches, restores dropped/mutated batches),
and removes session state.
.B WARNING:
This will undo any commits made during the session.
.SS File-Level Operations
.TP
.B include \-\-file
Stage all hunks from the selected file.
Advances to the next file after staging all hunks.
.TP
.B skip \-\-file
Skip all hunks from the selected file.
All hunks from the file are marked as skipped and can be revisited with
.BR again .
.TP
.B discard \-\-file
Discard the entire selected file from the working tree.
.B WARNING:
This permanently removes the entire file from your working tree.
.SS Line-Level Operations
.TP
.B include \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR
Stage only specific lines from the selected hunk.
Lines are displayed with IDs in brackets (e.g., [#1], [#2]).
LINE_IDS syntax: single (1), multiple (1,3,5), range (5-7), or combined (1,3,5-7).
After processing, the hunk is recalculated to show remaining changes.
.TP
.B skip \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR
Mark specific lines as skipped without staging them.
Useful when you want to defer certain changes to a later commit.
.TP
.B discard \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR
Remove specific lines from the working tree.
.B WARNING:
This permanently removes the specified lines from your working tree.
Allows surgical removal of debug code or unwanted modifications.
.SS Permanent File Exclusion
.TP
.B block-file \fR[\fIPATH\fR]
Permanently exclude a file from all future sessions.
Adds the file to .gitignore, marks it as blocked in session state,
and skips all its hunks automatically.
When run without a selected hunk, you can specify the file path.
.TP
.B unblock-file \fIPATH\fR
Remove a file from the blocked list.
Removes the file from .gitignore and the blocked files list,
allowing its hunks to be processed again.
.SS Fixup Suggestions
.TP
.B suggest-fixup \fR[\fIOPTIONS\fR] [\fIBOUNDARY\fR]
Suggest which commit the selected hunk should be fixed up to.
Finds commits that previously modified the lines in the selected hunk
and suggests them as fixup targets. Iteratively shows candidates starting
from most recent, progressing backwards with each invocation.
Uses git log -L to find commits that touched the affected lines.
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR
Suggest fixup target for specific lines only.
Useful when a hunk contains changes to multiple unrelated areas.
.TP
.B \-\-reset
Start over from the most recent candidate.
.TP
.B \-\-abort
Clear state and exit without showing candidates.
.TP
.B \-\-last
Re-show the last candidate without advancing.
.TP
.B \-\-porcelain
Output in machine-readable JSON format for script integration.
The JSON includes: candidate (hash, full_hash, subject, author, date,
relative_date), iteration number, and boundary.
.RE
.SH ADVANCED FEATURES
.SS Batch Operations
Batches are named collections of accumulated changes that can be staged or
discarded later as a unit. This is a power-user feature for complex workflows
involving deferred decisions across multiple files or staging passes.
.PP
Most users will not need batches. They are useful when you want to:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Accumulate related changes across multiple hunks for review together
.IP \(bu 2
Defer changes without losing them while you work on other commits
.IP \(bu 2
Group changes by type (e.g., debugging, refactoring) for separate handling
.RE
.PP
Batches are stored as git commits under refs/batches/<name> and persist
across sessions until explicitly dropped.
.TP
.B new \fIBATCH_NAME\fR [\fB\-\-note\fR \fINOTE\fR]
Create a new named batch for accumulating changes.
.TP
.B list
List all existing batches with their descriptions.
.TP
.B drop \fIBATCH_NAME\fR
Delete a batch and remove its git ref.
.TP
.B annotate \fIBATCH_NAME\fR \fINOTE\fR
Add or update the description for a batch.
.PP
The following commands accept \fB\-\-from\fR flags to work with batches:
.TP
.B show \-\-from \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR]
Show the accumulated changes stored in a batch.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to filter display to specific line IDs.
.TP
.B include \-\-from \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR]
Stage the changes from a batch to the index. Fails if the batch's changes
cannot be applied cleanly to the selected state.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to stage only specific lines from the batch.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR to apply all hunks from the batch that affect the selected file.
.TP
.B discard \-\-from \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR]
Remove batch changes from the working tree. Fails if the batch's changes
cannot be reversed cleanly. Does not delete the batch.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to discard only specific lines from the batch.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR to reverse all hunks from the batch that affect the selected file.
.TP
.B apply \-\-from \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR]
Apply batch changes to the working tree without staging them.
This adds the batch's changes to your working tree while keeping the index clean.
Fails if the batch's changes cannot be applied cleanly.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to apply only specific lines from the batch.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR to apply all hunks from the batch that affect the selected file.
.PP
The following commands accept \fB\-\-to\fR flags to save changes to batches:
.TP
.B include \-\-to \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR]
Save the selected hunk to a batch instead of just skipping it.
Auto-creates the batch if it doesn't exist.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to save only specific lines to the batch.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR to save the entire selected file to the batch.
.TP
.B discard \-\-to \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR]
Save the selected hunk to a batch, then discard it from the working tree.
Auto-creates the batch if it doesn't exist.
Useful for saving changes before removing them, allowing later recovery.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to save and discard only specific lines.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR to save and discard the entire selected file.
